  <datafield tag="520" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Since the LISE ++ code presentation at the EMIS 2007 conference (Tarasov and Bazin, 2008), important improvements have been made in the analytical and Monte Carlo calculations of transmission, and accuracy of reaction product distributions. In this paper new features of the code in ion-beam optics, creation of new LISE ++ blocks, and development of some reaction models will be discussed. Large progress has been done in ion-beam optics with the introduction of “elemental” blocks, that allows optical matrices calculation within LISE ++ . New type of configurations based on these blocks allow a detailed analysis of the transmission, useful for fragment separator design, and can be used for optics optimization based on user constraints.</subfield>
